"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901447","Home Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>All claims for asylum are considered on their individual merits in line with Home Office guidance, and where people establish a genuine need for protection, or a well founded fear of persecution, refugee status will be granted.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901447/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-22T11:28:33.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901447/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901447/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-10","Asylum: Vietnam","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the reported incident of a Home Office caseworker using a Lonely Planet guide to determine how safe it would be for an asylum applicant to return to Ho Chi Minh City.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL7773"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901448","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>The UK has concerns about the revocation of nationality when it renders a person stateless. We have raised this at a senior level with the Government of Bahrain.</p><p>The British Embassy in Bahrain and the Foreign and Commonwealth Office continue to monitor the cases of family members of Mr Alwadaei. We have raised the cases at a senior level with the Government of Bahrain.</p><p>We encourage those with concerns about treatment in detention to report these to the appropriate oversight bodies and we encourage these oversight bodies to carry out swift and thorough investigations. We understand that there have been communications between Mr Alwadaei and the oversight bodies in Bahrain on these cases.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901448/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-22T11:44:03.967Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901448/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901448/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Sayed Alwadaei","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Bahrain in relation to the judicial harassment of Sayed Ahmed Alwadaei and his family members, in particular (1) the revocation of Mr Alwadaei’s citizenship in 2015 that rendered him stateless, and (2) the torture and imprisonment of his family members.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL7774"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901449","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>Our programmes undergo continual assessment throughout their implementation, to ensure that they are on track for delivery, as well as upon completion of each individual project. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office has provided numerous updates on its programme work in its annual Human Rights Reports, as well as through Freedom of Information Act requests. This information can be found on the gov.uk website.</p><p>The Government works with a number of implementation partners and beneficiaries to support Bahraini-led reform. These programmes aim to support progress on building effective and accountable institutions, strengthening the rule of law, and justice reform. All of our work is in line with international standards and aims to share the UK's expertise and experience. Any training provided by or on behalf of the British Government fully complies with its domestic and international human rights obligations. The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is not in a position to make precise details available as it has a duty to maintain the confidentiality and confidence of its partners.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901449/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-22T11:47:55.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901449/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901449/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Bahrain: Technical Assistance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure transparency while providing funding for technical assistance to Bahrain; and who have been the beneficiaries of the Integrated Activity Fund and Global Britain Fund.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL7775"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901450","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-22","<p>Overall spend from the Gulf Strategy Integrated Activity Fund (IAF) in financial year 2016/17 was £5,786,905. The IAF funded activity in all six Gulf States: Kuwait, Saudi Arabia, Bahrain, Qatar, the United Arab Emirates and Oman. As many of the projects and programme activities are delivered regionally, it is not possible to provide a breakdown by beneficiary state</p><p />",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901450/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-22T11:48:44.65Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901450/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901450/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Gulf States: Overseas Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the overall spend for the Integrated Activity Fund in financial year 2016–17; which countries have benefited from that fund; and what was the breakdown of the spending for each beneficiary state.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL7776"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901451","Department for Education","false","2018-05-24","<p>As the Noble Lord, Lord Scriven, notes, the University of Huddersfield is an independent, autonomous body responsible for the development of the courses it offers. The university was selected by Bahrain’s Royal Academy of Policing to provide an MSc course in security science and this is a private arrangement between these parties.</p><p> </p><p>I can confirm, however, that support for the MSc in security science has not been provided by the Department for Education, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office or the Home Office.</p>",,"Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901451/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-24T16:06:46.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901451/answer","Biography information for Viscount Younger of Leckie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901451/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Police: Bahrain","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have provided financial or any other types of support to the University of Huddersfield’s new masters course in Security Science for Bahrain’s Royal Academy of Policing.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL7777"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901452","Department for Education","false","2018-05-24","<p>Since 18 September 2017, data on children’s centres has been supplied by local authorities via the department’s Get Information about Schools database portal at: <a href="https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://www.get-information-schools.service.gov.uk/</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The figures in the table below are based on information supplied by local authorities as at 11 May 2018[1].</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of children’s centres closed</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>182</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>135</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>12</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>1 April to 11 May 2018</p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>A list of the children’s centres that have closed in each financial year since April 2015 is attached.</p><p> </p><p>Councils are reconfiguring services to deliver them more efficiently. If a council decides to close a children’s centre, statutory guidance is clear that they should demonstrate that local children and families would not be adversely affected and that local areas continue to have sufficient children’s centres to meet their needs.</p><p> </p><p>Over the same period, the number of two, three and four years olds in good and outstanding early years provision has increased, as set out in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>[1] Based on information supplied by local authorities as at 11 May 2018, 11:30 am. These figures may be different to previous answers, and could change again in future, since local authorities may update the database at any time.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901452/answer","HL7778_Childrens_Centres_closures_since_April_2015.xlsx ; HL7778_2_3_and_4_year_olds_in_good_or_outstanding_early_years_provision.docx","HL7778_Childrens_Centres_closures_since_April_2015.xlsx ; HL7778_2_3_and_4_year_olds_in_good_or_outstanding_early_years_provision.docx","Childrens_Centres_closures_since_April_2015 ; 2_3_and_4_year_olds_in_good_or_outstanding_EY","Childrens_Centres_closures_since_April_2015 ; 2_3_and_4_year_olds_in_good_or_outstanding_EY",,"2018-05-24T16:01:49.933Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901452/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901452/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-10","Children's Centres: Closures","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many and which Children's Centres closed in 2015–16, 2016–17 and 2017 to date.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL7778"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901453","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-24","<p>This Government recognises the crucial role which UK manufacturers and producers play in our economy. We are committed to ensuring that UK industry has the protections it needs against injury caused by unfair trading practices. We are working to set up the Trade Remedies Authority by the time the UK leaves the EU – to ensure that the UK can continue to provide a safety net to domestic industries.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901453/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-24T11:10:37.427Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901453/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901453/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-10","Trade Remedies Authority","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether a Trade Remedies Authority will be set up before the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901454","Department for International Trade","false","2018-05-24","<p>The UK is committed to a rules based international trade system and is in the process of establishing the Trade Remedies Authority to ensure that UK businesses continue to be protected from unfair and injurious trade practices once we leave the EU.</p><p> </p><p>The UK, will be able, as the EU currently can, to pursue an appeal against trade remedies measures imposed on UK goods, in line with the domestic processes in the country imposing measures against UK goods.</p><p> </p><p>The Government will also be able to bring a case to WTO dispute settlement over measures that are not compliant with WTO agreements.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901454/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-24T11:10:08.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901454/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901454/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-05-10","Trade Remedies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have set up the appeal mechanism required under World Trade Organization rules which will enable the UK to challenge trade defence measures taken by other countries against UK goods.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901455","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-17","<p>We have continued to build on the progress we made at March European Council, by jointly publishing the topics for discussion on the future framework. This incorporates both the economic and security partnerships outlined by the Prime Minister.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The Government is clear that we must do whatever is most practical and pragmatic to provide security for our citizens. We therefore intend to develop a new security partnership with the EU that builds on the breadth and depth of our shared interests and values, and thus goes beyond any existing third country arrangements. We want to continue to cooperate with the EU on all aspects of our security relationship from foreign and defence policy, to law enforcement and criminal judicial cooperation.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901455/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-17T12:11:29.36Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901455/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901455/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-10","National Security","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have made progress in securing a Brexit deal on security.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL7781"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901456","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-22","<p>Currently there are 908 registered sign language interpreters, and 234 trainee interpreters.</p><p>It is estimated there are currently at least 24,000 people in the UK for whom British Sign Language (BSL) is their first language.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901456/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-22T11:01:42.587Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901456/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901456/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-10","Sign Language","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many (1) registered sign language interpreters, and (2) sign language users, there are in the UK.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL7782"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901457","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-24","<p>Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport (DCMS) has received representations on access to a video relay service. This includes recent correspondence from Jim Fitzpatrick MP (Chair of the All-Party Parliamentary Group on Deafness) in relation to changing existing legislation to expand Ofcom’s remit to include the regulation of Captioned Telephone Relay and Video Relay Services.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901457/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-24T11:11:00.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901457/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901457/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-10","Hearing Impairment: Telecommunications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have received from (1) sign language users, and (2) organisations representing deaf people, concerning a free to access video relay service.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL7783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901458","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-22","<p>Contact Scotland was launched in 2016 for calls via video relay service to public sector bodies only. In 2017 the ability to call third sector organisations via video relay service was added.</p><p> </p><p>Contact Scotland will be able to provide further information and advise on take-up of the service and can be contacted either by calling 0141 419 0420 or emailing them at: <a href="mailto:info@contactscotland-bsl.org" target="_blank">info@contactscotland-bsl.org</a>.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to look at lessons from developments in Scotland to inform our thinking for England and Wales.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901458/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-22T11:08:06.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901458/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901458/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-10","Hearing Impairment: Telecommunications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the take up in Scotland of free to access video relay service for public services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL7784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901459","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-05-22","<p>Under the EU Universal Service Directive, Member States must ensure that access to, and affordability of, voice telephony for end-users with disabilities is equivalent to the level enjoyed by the majority of end-users.</p><p> </p><p>In the UK, the Directive is implemented through the Communications Act and the Universal Service Order. The Order requires Ofcom to ensure the provision of relay services (defined as providing facilities for the receipt and translation of voice messages into text and text into voice messages).</p><p> </p><p>The Government has not made any formal assessment of costs of providing a national free to access video relay service in England.</p><p> </p><p>We are aware of international comparisons with other countries, for example, Australia, Canada and the USA, where video relay service is provided for free to users and costs between £0.48 and £2.62 per citizen per year, plus state-level levies where relevant. There are a range of funding models, including general taxation and levies on communication providers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government's position is that a voluntary approach to video relay should be followed and not a mandatory approach funded by taxation or general levies.</p>",,"Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901459/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-22T11:11:16.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901459/answer","Biography information for Baroness Buscombe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901459/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-05-10","Hearing Impairment: Telecommunications","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the cost of providing a national free to access video relay service in England; and whether they are considering setting up such a service for public services.","false","Biography information for Baroness Thomas of Winchester",,"Baroness Thomas of Winchester","HL7785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901460","Department for International Development","false","2018-05-17","<p>The UK concentrates its humanitarian efforts in Syria on helping those most acutely in need. We have now committed £2.71 billion to the Syria Crisis to date, our largest ever response to a single humanitarian crisis. Of this, £2.3 billion has already been allocated by DFID to implementing partners including £910 million for humanitarian projects in Syria, and over £1.4 billion for projects in the region supporting Syrian refugees and host communities. DFID is currently funding 15 agencies implementing projects in Syria, including UN agencies, international NGOs, and some private sector companies.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2012, our support has provided life-saving support to millions of Syrians, including over 22 million food rations, 9.9 million medical consultations, and over 9 million relief packages across Syria.</p>",,"Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901460/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-17T16:42:10.973Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901460/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901460/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-05-10","Syria: Humanitarian Aid","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Earl Howe on 3 May (HL7372), what is the criteria for the delivery of the UK's £2.71 billion in humanitarian aid to the people of Syria; how it is allocated; and who will receive it.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL7786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901461","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-23","<p>The UK remains committed to supporting Syrian Civil Defence (also known as the White Helmets) and the vital work they do providing life-saving assistance to civilians affected by Syria's conflict.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901461/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-23T14:21:51.12Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901461/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901461/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-10","Syria: White Helmets","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will re-consider their financial support for the White Helmets in Syria following the United States' suspension of its funding.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL7787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/902097","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-16","<p>All land-owning departments and arms-length bodies are required to take steps to regularly review their estates and delivery plans to identify land suitable for disposal, including for housing use, via the Public Land for Housing programme.</p><p>Release of land contributes to the Government's target of building 300,000 homes annually by the mid 2020s. Not all central government land is suitable for housing, but may be suitable for other operational purposes, such as new health facilities or schools.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/902097/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-16T15:04:33.877Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/902097/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/902097/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-10","Government Departments: Land","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that Government departments and their agencies release land for the provision of new homes.","false","Biography information for John Howell","Henley","John Howell","905326"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900288","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-09","<p>I recently held bilateral discussions with party leaders in Belfast to talk about next steps in Northern Ireland and I will meet the parties again shortly. During our discussions, I reviewed the current position with them and explored how the restoration of devolution might be achieved while ensuring the good governance of Northern Ireland in the interim.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900288/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-09T13:04:20.043Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900288/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900288/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","Northern Ireland Government","1","House of Commons","What progress has been made on restoring devolved government in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Alan Mak","Havant","Alan Mak","905149"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900289","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-09","<p>This government has presided over a period where Economic output in Northern Ireland continues to rise, and the export market has rapidly expanded. Unemployment levels are close to an all-time low, and 52,000 more people are in work compared to 2010. The recent announcement by Bombardier is yet another example of growth in the economy.</p><p>In my engagements across Northern Ireland I am consistently impressed by the talent and expertise on offer. However, there are crucial economic challenges to address and a restored Executive is essential to make the key strategic decisions needed to advance the Northern Ireland Economy.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900289/answer",,,,,"905156","2018-05-09T14:06:49.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900289/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900289/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","Economic Growth: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","What recent assessment she has made of the level of growth in the Northern Ireland economy.","false","Biography information for Edward Argar","Charnwood","Edward Argar","905151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900290","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-09","<p>The UK as a whole will be leaving the Customs Union.</p><p>This Government is committed to delivering a Brexit that upholds the Belfast Agreement and the commitments that we have made to the people of Northern Ireland to avoid a hard border with Ireland and any border down the Irish Sea.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900290/answer",,,,,"905154","2018-05-09T14:07:52.373Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900290/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900290/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","What the Government's policy is on customs arrangements on the island of Ireland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Ged Killen","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Ged Killen","905152"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900291","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-09","<p>No Northern Ireland Office employee earns less than the living wage - £10.20 in London and £8.75 outside London.</p><p>The Northern Ireland Office is aligned to the Ministry of Justice for terms and conditions including pay.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900291/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-09T12:14:29.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900291/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900291/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","Northern Ireland Office: Low Pay","1","House of Commons","What steps she is taking to improve wages and conditions for staff in her Department who are on low pay.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","905153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900292","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-09","<p>The UK as a whole will be leaving the Customs Union.</p><p>This Government is committed to delivering a Brexit that upholds the Belfast Agreement and the commitments that we have made to the people of Northern Ireland to avoid a hard border with Ireland and any border down the Irish Sea.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900292/answer",,,,,"905152","2018-05-09T14:07:52.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900292/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900292/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","UK Trade with EU: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","What assessment she has made of the potential merits of Northern Ireland remaining in the Customs Union.","false","Biography information for Christine Jardine","Edinburgh West","Christine Jardine","905154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900293","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-09","<p>This government has presided over a period where Economic output in Northern Ireland continues to rise, and the export market has rapidly expanded. Unemployment levels are close to an all-time low, and 52,000 more people are in work compared to 2010. The recent announcement by Bombardier is yet another example of growth in the economy.</p><p>In my engagements across Northern Ireland I am consistently impressed by the talent and expertise on offer. However, there are crucial economic challenges to address and a restored Executive is essential to make the key strategic decisions needed to advance the Northern Ireland Economy.</p><p> </p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900293/answer",,,,,"905151","2018-05-09T14:06:49.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900293/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900293/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","Economic Growth: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","What recent assessment she has made of the level of growth in the Northern Ireland economy.","false","Biography information for Maggie Throup","Erewash","Maggie Throup","905156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900302","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-05-10","<p>We are keen to support the Scottish Government through its current procurement and continue to provide every assistance to deliver Superfast broadband along with new fibre networks to Scotland. The Secretary of State recently appeared before the Scottish Affairs committee to discuss digital connectivity in Scotland.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, officials from the department have had regular meetings with their counterparts at the Scottish Government including providing technical advice and guidance to the Scottish Government programme team.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900302/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-10T15:19:36.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900302/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900302/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-05-09","Broadband: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions he has had with the Scottish Government on access to broadband in remote parts of Scotland.","false","Biography information for Jamie Stone","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Jamie Stone","905200"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900348","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-14","<p>Since August 2017, new undergraduate nursing, midwifery and some allied health profession students are able to access loans through the standard student support system.</p><p> </p><p>A number of provisions are available to support these students whilst undertaking the clinical placement element of their courses. These include child dependants allowance, travel and dual accommodation support and, in eligible cases, an exceptional hardship fund. Allowing students to access the student loans system also enables them to be up to 25% better off while they study than under the previous funding system.</p><p> </p><p>From August 2018 new postgraduate pre-registration students and most new undergraduate pre-registration dental hygiene and dental therapy students will also be able to access loans through the standard student support system. This change will allow eligible students to access child dependants allowance, travel and dual accommodation support and, in eligible cases, an exceptional hardship fund.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will also put in place incentives for postgraduate healthcare students who go on to work in the healthcare sector - such as 'golden' hellos for postgraduates who go on to work in mental health and learning disability fields and those postgraduates who go on to work in community nursing roles. The Department will provide up to £10 million to support this.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900348/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T11:58:48.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900348/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900348/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-09","Health Professions: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what support his Department provides to people studying healthcare courses; whether he plans to provide further support for those people's (a) living costs and (b) course fees; and if he will make statement.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","142450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900349","Home Office","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Home Office uses private companies to provide detention facilities for immigration purposes, as well for the provision of escorting and travel services in relation to Removals.</p><p>The operating costs for each of these contracts is commercially confidential and public disclosure would prejudice the commercial interests of the Home Office and its suppliers. However, the Home Office publishes payments in excess of £25K on its website at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/home-office-spending" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/home-office-spending</a></p><p>The data available on the link above covers the period up to the end of January 2017. Further transparency spend data will be uploaded to this web address by July 2018.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900349/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T14:53:28.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900349/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900349/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-09","Immigrants: Detainees","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what payments his Department has made to private companies for (a) keeping people in custody and detention and (b) deporting people in relation to immigration cases in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Angus Brendan MacNeil","Na h-Eileanan an Iar","Angus Brendan MacNeil","142377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900350","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-17","<p>We are improving the parole system following the Review of the law, policy and procedures relating to Parole Board decision making – which was published on 28 April. We will allow victims and others to receive summaries of Parole Board decisions; we are consulting on a mechanism to allow for decisions to be reconsidered; and will review the Parole Board rules in their entirety. This will improve the transparency and robustness of the parole process and the experience of victims.</p><p> </p><p>We have no current plans to change the legislation to restrict or take away the possibility of prisoners being considered for parole where that is part of the sentence the courts have given them.</p><p> </p><p>A prisoner is entitled to review by the Parole Board once they have completed the punitive part of their sentence (at tariff expiry) and at periods not exceeding two years thereafter. The Parole Board may only direct the release an offender if satisfied they do not pose a risk to the safety of the public. Whilst a prisoner might have multiple opportunities to go before the Parole Board they will only be released when the Board considers it safe to do so. Where a further offence is committed by an offender released on licence that would be a factor considered by the Board in any future parole hearing.</p><p> </p><p>Any restriction on an offender’s ability to have their continued detention considered once they are only serving the preventative part of the sentence (post tariff) would be unlawful. Their detention would then become arbitrary and it would effectively apply a whole-life order to the offender – which would be disproportionate and unjustified by the sentence imposed by the court.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900350/answer",,,,,"142379","2018-05-17T16:28:09.573Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900350/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900350/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-09","Parole","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will bring forward proposals to restrict the right of prisoners to be eligible for parole on multiple occasions.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","142378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900351","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-17","<p>We are improving the parole system following the Review of the law, policy and procedures relating to Parole Board decision making – which was published on 28 April. We will allow victims and others to receive summaries of Parole Board decisions; we are consulting on a mechanism to allow for decisions to be reconsidered; and will review the Parole Board rules in their entirety. This will improve the transparency and robustness of the parole process and the experience of victims.</p><p> </p><p>We have no current plans to change the legislation to restrict or take away the possibility of prisoners being considered for parole where that is part of the sentence the courts have given them.</p><p> </p><p>A prisoner is entitled to review by the Parole Board once they have completed the punitive part of their sentence (at tariff expiry) and at periods not exceeding two years thereafter. The Parole Board may only direct the release an offender if satisfied they do not pose a risk to the safety of the public. Whilst a prisoner might have multiple opportunities to go before the Parole Board they will only be released when the Board considers it safe to do so. Where a further offence is committed by an offender released on licence that would be a factor considered by the Board in any future parole hearing.</p><p> </p><p>Any restriction on an offender’s ability to have their continued detention considered once they are only serving the preventative part of the sentence (post tariff) would be unlawful. Their detention would then become arbitrary and it would effectively apply a whole-life order to the offender – which would be disproportionate and unjustified by the sentence imposed by the court.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900351/answer",,,,,"142378","2018-05-17T16:28:09.653Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900351/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900351/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-09","Life Imprisonment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will bring forward proposals to ensure that prisoners released on parole from life sentences are ineligible for parole again in the event that they re-offend.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","142379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900352","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-17","<p>The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost. The latest regularly published information on releases in error can be found within the NOMS Annual Digest 2016/17 <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/annual-national-offender-management-service-digest-2016-to-2017</a></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900352/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-17T16:38:03.487Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900352/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900352/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-09","Prisoners' Release","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many prisoners convicted of what offence and with what period of sentence left to serve who were released from prison in error (a) have and (b) have not been returned to custody in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","142380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900353","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-17","<p>Annual data is available in the ‘Criminal Justice Statistics Outcomes by Offence’ tool in Criminal Justice Statistics publication which can be found at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/criminal-justice-system-statistics-quarterly-december-2016</a></p><p>Offences of sexual activity with a child under 13 and of sexual activity involving a child under 16 can be selected from the offence drop down box. Drop down boxes are also available for gender and age group.</p><p>Data on female offenders is not available prior to 2015 due to recording issues.</p><p>Data for 2017 is planned for publication later in May 2018.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900353/answer",,,,,"142382","2018-05-17T16:37:19.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900353/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900353/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-09","Offences against Children: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many and what proportion of (a) men and (b) women convicted of sexual activity with a child received a prison sentence in each of the last five years; and what the average prison sentence was for such (i) men and (ii) women.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","142381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900354","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Government recognises the valuable contribution made by carers who spend a significant proportion of their life providing unpaid support to friends and family members, including those who are ill or have disabilities. That is why the Government is committed to continuing to support carers, who are vital partners in the health and care system, and will continue to support carers in a way that supports their own health and wellbeing, employment and other life chances.</p><p> </p><p>The Department will shortly be publishing a Carers Action Plan, setting out a cross-Government programme of targeted work to support carers over the next two years. Within the Action Plan there will be a chapter dedicated to carers in employment which will cover improving working practices, flexible working and returning to work.</p><p> </p><p>The Department has also been working with the Timewise Foundation on a project to promote best practice in the use of employment flexibilities to support carers. Last month, Timewise launched a new Carers’ Hub – a one-stop shop for support, advice and flexible job opportunities to help carers balance their responsibilities with fulfilling careers, as well as offering best practice guidance on flexible working and flexible hiring practices, in order to help employers find and keep talented people who want or need to work in this way.</p><p> </p><p>More information about the Carers’ hub can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.timewisejobs.co.uk/caring/" target="_blank">https://www.timewisejobs.co.uk/caring/</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900354/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T15:27:13.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900354/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900354/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-09","Employment: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to improve awareness among employers of the extra burdens felt by employees who are carers.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","142451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900355","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-14","<p>Skills for Care publishes projections of the adult social care workforce and forecasts the number of adult social care jobs could increase by 31% (500,000 jobs) to around two million jobs by 2030.</p><p> </p><p>The Department is aware that our challenge, working alongside stakeholders in the adult social care sector, is to ensure the workforce has the right number of people to meet increasing demands, with the right skills, knowledge and behaviours to deliver quality, compassionate care.</p><p> </p><p>That is why we consulted the sector on the draft Health and Social Care Workforce Strategy. The results of the consultation will inform both the final strategy and the Green Paper on care and support for older people, both due later this year.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900355/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T15:20:08.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900355/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900355/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-09","Social Services: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate his Department has made of the number of additional social care workers that will be required by 2030; and what steps he is taking to ensure that need is met.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","142452"
