"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900585","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>Admission arrangements for individual schools are set and applied locally, as such, the Department does not hold information around the outcome of individual applications.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise that looked after children are amongst the most vulnerable in our society and, wherever possible, should be admitted to the school which is best able to meet their needs. That is why the School Admissions Code requires admission authorities of all schools, including academies, to give highest priority in their admissions criteria to looked-after children and previously looked after children.</p><p> </p><p>Where a school refuses to admit looked-after or previously looked after children, they can be directed to do so.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900585/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T16:50:09.857Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900585/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900585/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-09","Children in Care: Academies","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many looked-after children were refused a place at an academy school in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","142462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900586","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-05-14","<p>The funding and delivery of National Health Service bereavement services, including the training of staff, is a local matter.</p><p>Bereavement care is a key part of the provision of good end of life care as set out in the Government’s end of life care Choice Commitment, published in July 2016. As part of this, Health Education England, in partnership with Skills for Care and Skills for Health, published a refreshed End of Life Care Core Skills Education and Training Framework in March 2017. This aims to standardise end of life care training and education, including around bereavement care. The Government’s Choice Commitment and the framework can be found at the following links:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/publications/choice-in-end-of-life-care-government-response" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/publications/choice-in-end-of-life-care-government-response</a></p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.skillsforhealth.org.uk/services/item/536-end-of-life-care-cstf-download" target="_blank">www.skillsforhealth.org.uk/services/item/536-end-of-life-care-cstf-download</a></p><p> </p><p>The importance of bereavement care is also reflected in the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) Quality Standard on end of life care, and other NICE end of life care guidance, which commissioners should take into account when planning services for local populations. The Quality Standard, which highlights that children may need specific tailored support to help them with bereavement, can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.nice.org.uk/guidance/qs13" target="_blank">www.nice.org.uk/guidance/qs13</a></p><p> </p><p>The Quality Standard draws on a range of evidence, including older Departmental guidance such as When a person dies: guidance for professionals on developing bereavement services, first published by the Department in 2005, and updated in 2011 by the Primary Care Commissioning Service with support from the NHS National End of Life Care Programme and the Bereavement Services Association. The guidance can be found at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.pcc-cic.org.uk/sites/default/files/articles/attachments/when_a_person_dies_19_oct_2011.pdf" target="_blank">www.pcc-cic.org.uk/sites/default/files/articles/attachments/when_a_person_dies_19_oct_2011.pdf</a></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900586/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T15:25:17.23Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900586/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900586/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-05-09","Bereavement Counselling: Children and Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what (a) financial support (b) guidance and (c) training his Department provides to child bereavement services to ensure appropriate support for children and young people.","true","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","142453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900587","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-17","<p>We are in the process of drafting guidance that will accompany the new regulations which will update the laws on the selling of animals as pets, including online. This will be available in due course and well before the new regulations come into force on 1 October. The guidance will be available to local authorities and all vendors of pet animals.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900587/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-17T15:48:23.31Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900587/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900587/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-09","Animals: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what guidance his Department has issued to online marketplaces on the regulations that apply the sale of animals.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","142320"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900588","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-05-17","<p>The Government shares the British public’s high regards for animal welfare and, after we leave the EU, the Government plans to retain the current regulations banning the import of cat and dog fur and products, and seal skins and products from commercial hunts.</p><p>The Government has pressed for higher animal welfare standards worldwide to phase out cruel and inhumane fur farming and trapping practices in other parts of the world, which are banned here.</p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900588/answer",,,,,"142350","2018-05-17T16:04:56.827Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900588/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900588/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-05-09","Furs: Sales","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential merits of extending the ban on the sale of cat, dog and seal fur to other species.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","142321"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900589","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) currently offers apprenticeships at Levels 2 to 6 and plans to also offer apprenticeships at Level 7.</p><p> </p><p>BEIS was formed in July 2016. The table below shows apprenticeship starts from July 2016 to March 2017 and for 2017-18.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Level 2</p></td><td><p>Level 3</p></td><td><p>Level 4</p></td><td><p>Level 5</p></td><td><p>Level 6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>2</p></td><td><p>8</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>-</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017-18</p></td><td><p>-</p></td><td><p>4</p></td><td><p>30</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>2</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Watford","Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900589/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T16:33:39.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900589/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900589/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-05-09","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what levels of apprenticeship his Department offers; and how many apprenticeship starts there were at each level in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","142422"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900590","Cabinet Office","false","2018-06-20","<p>Apprenticeships in Cabinet Office can be started at levels intermediate, advanced, higher and degree.</p><p> </p><p>Overall apprenticeship starts in the Cabinet Office in England were as follows in each of the last three years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>Intermediate</p></td><td><p>Advanced</p></td><td><p>Higher</p></td><td><p>Degree</p></td><td><p>% of workforce</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2015 – March 2016</p></td><td><p>55</p></td><td colspan="4"><p>Data not available</p></td><td><p>2.5%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2016 – March 2017</p></td><td><p>53</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>25</p></td><td><p>28</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>1.98%</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2017 – December 2017</p></td><td><p>27</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>11</p></td><td><p>16</p></td><td><p>0</p></td><td><p>0.52%</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Please note that we are awaiting finalised data for the period January-March 2018.</p><p> </p><p>Note that apprentice starts outside England were</p><p> </p><p>With the introduction of the apprenticeship levy in May 2017 our trajectory assumes slower growth at the beginning with starts increasing over time. This allows the necessary infrastructure to be put in place to ensure high quality apprenticeships are offered. The Cabinet Office contributes to the Civil Service commitment to deliver 30,000 new apprenticeship starts by 2020 with over 10,000 starts already achieved.</p><p> </p><p>The Cabinet Office recognises that apprenticeships are an effective means of employers developing their own talent and are a vital part of the Government’s plans to build a sustainable, balanced economy designed to extend opportunity to more young people. We are also contributing to the wider Government aims of tackling youth unemployment and inspiring young and ethnically-diverse people to see the Cabinet Office, and Civil Service, as an employer of choice.</p><p> </p><p>Cabinet Office is working to the Civil Service Apprenticeship Strategy and is offering apprenticeship opportunities where possible at all levels. This will be via new recruitment and the conversion of existing staff.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900590/answer",,,,,,"2018-06-20T09:49:33.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900590/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900590/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-05-09","Cabinet Office: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what levels of apprenticeships are offered by his Department; and how many apprenticeship starts there were at each level in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","142423"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900591","Home Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>We have reached an agreement with the EU on citizens’ rights that will protect those EU citizens and their family members who are lawfully resident in the UK by 31 December 2020. We will introduce a new settlement scheme under UK law for EU citizens and their family members to secure their rights under the Withdrawal Agreement.</p><p>Although not covered by citizens rights’ agreement with the EU, it is our intention that family members of UK nationals who have exercised their free movement rights in another EU Member State before returning to the UK before 31 December 2020, as per <em>Surinder Singh</em> case law, will be eligible to apply for the UK’s settlement scheme. We will provide details in advance of the scheme opening on the eligibility of those who benefit from the <em>Surinder Singh</em> judgment to apply for the settlement scheme.</p><p>Currently, non-EU born spouses of British citizens returning to the UK from another EU member state under the <em>Surinder Singh</em> judgment are not required to apply for a right of residence and therefore no estimate of numbers is available.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900591/answer",,,,,"142477","2018-05-15T13:26:00.057Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900591/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900591/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-09","Immigration: Married People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when he plans to issue guidance to UK citizens who are living with non-EU spouses in the UK under the Surinder Singh principle on their residence rights after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","142476"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900593","Home Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Home Office collects and publishes information on the number of persons detained under section 136 of the Mental Health Act 1983, at police force area level only.</p><p>These data were collected on a mandatory basis for the first time in 2016/17, and are published as part of the ‘Police powers and procedures, England and Wales’ statistical bulletin, which can be accessed here: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/police-powers-and-procedures-england-and-wales-year-ending-31-march-2017</a></p><p>Table MHA.05c of the accompanying data tables show that, in 2016/17, nobody was detained in a police station following a section 136 detention in the Merseyside police force area. In England, 898 people in total were detained in a police station following a section 136 detention.</p><p>Figures for 2015/16 were published by the National Police Chiefs’ Council and can be accessed using the following links:</p><p><a href="http://www.npcc.police.uk/documents/S136%20Data%202015%2016.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.npcc.police.uk/documents/S136%20Data%202015%2016.pdf</a>.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900593/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-15T11:59:15.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900593/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900593/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-09","Compulsorily Detained Psychiatric Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people detained under section 13 of the Mental Health Act 1983 were held in police cells in (a) Liverpool, Wavertree constituency, (b) Liverpool, (c) Liverpool City Region and (d) England in each in of the last two years.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","142435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900594","Home Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>We have reached an agreement with the EU on citizens’ rights that will protect those EU citizens and their family members who are lawfully resident in the UK by 31 December 2020. We will introduce a new settlement scheme under UK law for EU citizens and their family members to secure their rights under the Withdrawal Agreement.</p><p>Although not covered by citizens rights’ agreement with the EU, it is our intention that family members of UK nationals who have exercised their free movement rights in another EU Member State before returning to the UK before 31 December 2020, as per <em>Surinder Singh</em> case law, will be eligible to apply for the UK’s settlement scheme. We will provide details in advance of the scheme opening on the eligibility of those who benefit from the <em>Surinder Singh</em> judgment to apply for the settlement scheme.</p><p>Currently, non-EU born spouses of British citizens returning to the UK from another EU member state under the <em>Surinder Singh</em> judgment are not required to apply for a right of residence and therefore no estimate of numbers is available.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900594/answer",,,,,"142476","2018-05-15T13:26:00.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900594/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900594/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-09","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate his Department has made of the number of UK citizens with non-EU born spouses who have returned to the UK from another EU Member State under the Surinder Singh principle.","false","Biography information for Deidre Brock","Edinburgh North and Leith","Deidre Brock","142477"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900595","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-15","<p>I would refer the hon Member to my previous answer of 8 May 2018. The PSNI have been, and will continue to be, fully engaged in ongoing constructive meetings with representatives from both the Northern Ireland Office and other Whitehall departments on a wide range of matters, including the security implications of a hard border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland after the UK leaves the EU.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900595/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-15T14:32:24.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900595/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900595/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 8 May 2018 to Question 13996 on Security: Northern Ireland, on what dates the Police Service of Northern Ireland met with (a) Ministers and (b) officials of her Department to discuss the security implications of a hard border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","142366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900596","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>In February 2018, the government published ‘UK revenue from education related exports and transnational education activity 2015’. This estimated that international students at UK universities contributed £9.7 billion to the UK economy through tuition fees and living expenditure in 2015. The government does not, however, have an estimate of the regional contribution of international students on GDP and levels of unemployment.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900596/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T16:59:39.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900596/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900596/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-09","Overseas Students: North East","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment the Government made of the contribution of international students studying in North East Universities to that region's (a) GDP and (b) levels of unemployment.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","142443"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900597","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Ministry of Justice has considered the issues raised by the House of Lords Select Committee on the Mental Capacity Act 2005, and plans to publish a report on the use of section 44 by the end of this year.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900597/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T16:39:30.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900597/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900597/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-05-09","Mental Capacity Act 2005","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government plans to publish its review of section 44 of the Mental Capacity Act 2005.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","142444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900599","Department for Education","false","2018-05-14","<p>This government recognises the importance of mathematics skills, both in work and everyday life. We provide full funding for adults who need these skills to undertake a range of courses including GCSEs, Functional Skills and stepping stone qualifications up to level 2.</p><p> </p><p>Through the Flexible Learning Fund, we are investing over £11 million in a range of projects to design and test flexible and accessible ways of delivering learning to adults with low or intermediate skills. These projects include increasing the mathematics skills and confidence of adults already in work through online and blended learning techniques. We also fund Unionlearn to deliver projects develop the learning capacity, and skill and qualification amongst the workforce, with a particular focus on difficult to engage workers with low skills.</p><p> </p><p>We are reforming English and mathematics Functional Skills qualifications, which are accessed primarily by adults. This will make sure these qualifications are more rigorous and better recognised by employers.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900599/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T16:10:34.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900599/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900599/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-05-09","Numeracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to reduce the number of working age adults with poor numeracy skills.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","142445"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900600","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-05-14","<p>The Government has made clear that this should be a country that works for everyone, ensuring the housing market works for all parts of our community. The recent race disparity audit has shown only 41 per cent of ethnic minority households are homeowners, compared to 68 per cent of White British households. We are undertaking further research to understand the underlying issues and work to provide solutions to help increase homeownership among BAME communities.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900600/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-14T16:47:18.633Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900600/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900600/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-05-09","Owner Occupation: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what steps the Government is taking to promote home ownership among BAME communities.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","142446"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900601","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-15","<p>The Secretary of State meetings with PSNI Officers and Northern Ireland Office officials relate to matters concerning our exit from the EU. Release of this information while our exit from the EU is ongoing would indicate sensitive information relating to the negotiations. Ministers have a specific responsibility, which Parliament has endorsed, not to release information that could undermine our negotiating position.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900601/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-15T15:04:48.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900601/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900601/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-09","Security: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 8 May 2018 to Question 139996 on Security: Northern Ireland, if he will place in the Library copies of the redacted minutes of his briefings with (a) PSNI officers and (b) Northern Ireland Office officials during his visit to Northern Ireland of 23 April 2018.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","142367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900602","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-05-16","<p>Details of Ministerial meetings are published in the Department’s Quarterly Transparency Returns, which can be found on gov.uk.</p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900602/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-16T14:35:46.277Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900602/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900602/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-05-09","Department for Exiting the European Union: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 2 May 2018 to Question 137497 on Department for Exiting the European Union: Northern Ireland, if he will publish the programme of meetings and events for that visit.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","142368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900603","Northern Ireland Office","false","2018-05-16","<p>Any representations made to the Secretary of State by political parties regarding the salaries and allowances for Members of the Northern Ireland Assembly will be published by the Northern Ireland Office in due course, subject to any necessary redaction of sensitive or personal data.</p><p> </p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900603/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-16T14:13:07.89Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900603/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/900603/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2018-05-09","Northern Ireland Assembly: Members","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, pursuant to the Answer of 9 May 2018 to Question 140646 on Northern Ireland Assembly: Members, if she will place copies of the representations she received from political parties in Northern Ireland in the Library before Thursday 24 May 2018.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","142369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901024","Home Office","false","2018-05-23","<p>It is difficult to assess how many crimes have been perpetrated by or against people identifying as trans because the Home Office holds information on notifiable crimes reported to and recorded by the police but this does not include whether a victim or perpetrator of a crime identifies as trans.</p><p>In February 2018, the Office for National Statistics published articles on the natures of violent and sexual crime in England and Wales in 2016/17. These articles provide information on what we know about the victims and perpetrators of violent or sexual offences, but there are no figures for people identifying themselves as trans.</p><p>Individual forces may record information on transgender victims and perpetrators, but there is no current requirement for them to send such data to the Home Office as part of their regular data returns.</p><p>We want transgender people to be healthy, happy, and able to live their lives free from discrimination and distress and we are delivering on our commitment to review the Gender Recognition Act to move to a gender recognition system that works better for trans people.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901024/answer",,,,,"HL7669 ; HL7670 ; HL7672","2018-05-23T15:41:59.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901024/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/901024/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-05-09","Hate Crime: Females","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many offences against women perpetrated by people identifying as trans have been reported in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Baroness Barker",,"Baroness Barker","HL7668"
