"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/899962","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-05-21","<p>​Since 1990, the British Council has opened new offices for the first time in Switzerland, Rwanda, Namibia, Taiwan, and Mozambique. They also established offices in the newly independent states of Armenia, Azerbaijan, Belarus, Estonia, Georgia, Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, Latvia, Lithuania, Ukraine, Uzbekistan and Russia, after the break-up of the Soviet Union. Following the break-up of Yugoslavia, the British Council established offices in Bosnia-Herzegovina, Kosovo, the Republic of Macedonia, Montenegro and Slovenia; they also opened offices in the Czech Republic and Slovakia when they became independent states.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/899962/answer",,,,,,"2018-05-21T15:58:59.87Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/899962/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/899962/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-05-08","British Council","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which countries have had a British Council establishment opened since 1990.","false","Biography information for Lord McInnes of Kilwinning",,"Lord McInnes of Kilwinning","HL7625"
